<div class="container">
    <h1>Advanced Web App - Chapter Summary</h1>

    <p>In this chapter, we learned how to build more advanced web applications using ASP.NET Core. Here’s a recap of what we covered:</p>

    <h2>Main Topics</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Layers:</strong> Organizing your app into Controller, Service, and Repository layers to separate responsibilities.</li>
        <li><strong>Controller Layer:</strong> Handles user requests and returns responses.</li>
        <li><strong>Service Layer:</strong> Contains business logic, processes data, and applies rules before passing it to controllers.</li>
        <li><strong>Repository Layer:</strong> Manages data access and communicates with the database.</li>
        <li><strong>Identity & Roles:</strong> Using ASP.NET Core Identity to manage users, passwords, and roles.</li>
        <li><strong>Authentication:</strong> Securing your app by verifying users' identity.</li>
        <li><strong>Authorization:</strong> Controlling which users can access which parts of the app.</li>
        <li><strong>Identity Tutorial:</strong> Practical step-by-step guide to implement Identity in your app.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Exercises</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Create a small web app that uses three layers: Controller, Service, and Repository.</li>
        <li>Add a model (e.g., Product) and display a list of items on a page using the layers.</li>
        <li>Implement a simple authentication system using ASP.NET Core Identity.</li>
        <li>Add roles and authorization rules to restrict access to certain pages.</li>
        <li>Test your app to ensure that data flows correctly through layers and that authentication/authorization works as expected.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Once you complete these exercises, you will have a solid understanding of how advanced web applications are structured and secured.</p>

